-03|website=[[Haveeru]]}}</ref>
Professor Ugail is well known for his work on computer-based human face analysis including, face recognition,<ref name="halffacerecognition">{{cite web |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/05/190501114602.htm|title=Half a face enough for recognition technology|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> face ageing,<ref name="PrinceGeorgeFacePredicted">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-uk-future-face/prince-georges-future-face-predicted-by-scientists-idUSKCN0SZ1O420151110|title=Prince George's future face predicted by scientists|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref name="NewFaceAgeingTechnique">{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/new-face-ageing-technique-could-10622627|title=New face-ageing technique could boost search for missing people like Ben Needham and Maddy McCann|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> emotion analysis<ref name="LyingEyes">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robertglatter/2019/07/30/don-henley-was-right-you-cant-hide-your-lyin-eyes/|title=Don Henley Was Right: You Can't Hide Your Lying Eyes|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref name="FakeSmile">{{cite web |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/07/190729111239.htm|title=How can you reliably spot a fake smile? Ask a computer|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> and lie detection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-14900800|title=New emotion detector can see when we're lying|access-date=2019-08-12|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> For example, in 2018, he has used his face recognition tools to help unmask the two suspected Russian spies at the heart of the Salisbury Novichok poisoning case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/09/27/new-evidence-links-russian-state-to-berlin-assassination/|title=New Evidence Links Russian State to Berlin Assassination|access-date=2019-11-12|publisher=[[Belingcat]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/02/21/the-search-for-denis-sergeev-photogr